			<h3 id="Intro">Introduction</h3><b>About this course</b><br />Criminological Studies comprises a wide range of modules in sociology, law and psychology providing a multi-disciplinary approach to the study of criminal and deviant behaviour, crime, its regulation and control and criminal justice policy and practice. The programme will provide you with opportunities to consider why people commit crimes, exploring traditional and contemporary issues and will develop your understanding of crime, deviance and the criminal justice process. <br /><br />The programme will help you to ask questions about crimes and the people who allegedly commit them, such as â Who are the criminals? What do we mean by crime? What is criminology? How do we âtalkâ about crime? How do we define criminal behaviour? Who are the victims of crime? The different approaches taken in answering these questions will help to shape your understanding of the relationship between crime, politics and criminal justice policy.<br/><br/>	
		
		

			<h3 id="Themes">Core Themes</h3><b>What you study<br />Stage 1</b><br />The programme introduces key issues and concepts in understanding crime and criminal behaviour in criminology, sociology and psychology and research methods in sociology. In law, you will be provided with an opportunity to consider principles of law and the legal framework in Scotland and the UK. The first year will give you a general but extensive introduction to the relevant disciplines with a foundational approach that provides you with an opportunity to broaden your understanding of crime.<br />	<br /><b>Stage 2</b><br />You will analyse causes and explanations of crime through an introduction to theoretical approaches in sociology and criminology and their practical application to areas of social life and behaviour that may be perceived as affecting our understanding of crime and reactions to it. You will also explore the relationship between crime, power, class, age, gender and ethnicity.<br />	<br /><b>Stage 3</b><br />You will explore the control, prevention and regulation of crime from a historical perspective and assess the effectiveness of contemporary crime control strategies and interventions. At this stage, you will also have an opportunity to develop a broader understanding of the law and will be able to choose options in sociology of relevance to the programme.<br />	<br /><b>Stage 4</b><br />You will have the opportunity to reflect on contemporary competing approaches to the study of crime and to assess the effectiveness of these approaches and their application in the control and regulation of crime and criminal behaviours. You will also undertake an honours project at this level using a range of research methodologies to investigate a topic relevant to the study of crime and criminal behaviour.<br />	<br /><b>How you learn</b><br />	You will learn about crime through the use of lectures supported by tutorials and seminars. You will learn how to use library resources, develop basic skills in IT and develop reading and communication skills at each stage of the course. Generally you will be expected to attend one lecture and at least one tutorial for each module you study â a total of 8 hours class contact time per week.  In addition, the course offers occasional visits to criminal justice institutions and visiting speakers from criminal justice services are invited to present specific topics.<br />	<br /><b>How you are assessed</b><br />	The course is assessed in a variety of ways at each stage and in each module. The overall assessment strategy relies on assessing your progress through each stage using a complementary mixture of examinations, essay writing, class tests, module workbooks, oral presentations and tutorial exercises. Your progress is monitored and assessed throughout the course with feedback provided by returning marked coursework and test papers and in tutorial discussions.  Each unit of assessment may carry a specific percentage weighting of the total assessment grade.<br /><br />	
		
		
		

			<h3 id="Career">Career Opportunities:</h3>The course is designed to prepare you for associated careers in the prison service, policing, probation, social work and criminal justice practice. The inter-disciplinary nature of the course enables graduates to pursue a number of career routes, having gained skills and competence in the use of IT and in effectively gathering, evaluating and analysing data from a range of sources relevant to employment in the criminal justice and social work fields. Graduates from the programme are also encouraged to study at postgraduate level, the most typical courses being postgraduate teaching and Masters level study in criminal justice or social work policy â for which there is a demand, particularly in Scotland.<br /><br />	

		
