			<br /><h3>Transferable skills</h3>While studying on this course you will gain a number of practical skills that are useful in any field of business, such as how to use email, type reports, build a database, and use the internet effectively as well as being introduced to specialised software relevant to your subject choices.  You will also learn how to sift through vast quantities of detailed information quickly, and to present the important points in a concise and straightforward manner.  As you progress through the degree course you will gain other incidental skills which will prove invaluable in any future-working environment.  These may include:<br />1. Learning how to learn effectively<br />2. Self-motivation<br />3. Assertiveness<br />4. Time management<br />5. Meeting deadlines<br />6. Problem solving<br />7. Analysis, synthesis, discrimination and judgement<br />8. Logical and reasoned thinking.<br />	
			<br /><h3>Teamwork</h3>Being able to work as a member of a team is an important quality in a University student. Working in a team situation allows you to utilise your own personal strengths and to build upon areas where you are lacking by learning from other people.  It also allows you to gain experience in leading discussions and delegating responsibility, as well as learning to become an effective listener â an important leadership quality which can sometimes be overlooked. Making a positive contribution to a joint project allows you to develop team-working skills. <br />Working together on coursework often allows you to form close friendships in your social life as you learn to listen to and trust other peopleâs judgements.<br />	
		
		
		

		
